The red underline is caused by the wildcard generic types:

```java
RestClient.RequestHeadersUriSpec<?>
RestClient.RequestHeadersSpec<?>
```

Mockito cannot resolve the captured `?` type in `thenReturn(...)`.

Use `doReturn(...).when(...)` for these chained RestClient mocks.

```java
@Test
void shouldGetAppSuccessfully() {
    String appId = "B2BOOST_BE";
    AppConfigResponse expectedResponse = new AppConfigResponse();

    doReturn(requestHeadersUriSpec)
            .when(partnerRepoClient)
            .get();

    doReturn(requestHeadersSpec)
            .when(requestHeadersUriSpec)
            .uri(
                    "http://partner-repository/apps/{appId}",
                    appId
            );

    when(requestHeadersSpec.retrieve())
            .thenReturn(responseSpec);

    when(responseSpec.body(AppConfigResponse.class))
            .thenReturn(expectedResponse);

    AppConfigResponse result =
            partnerRepositoryClient.getApp(appId);

    assertSame(expectedResponse, result);

    verify(partnerRepoClient).get();
    verify(requestHeadersUriSpec).uri(
            "http://partner-repository/apps/{appId}",
            appId
    );
    verify(requestHeadersSpec).retrieve();
    verify(responseSpec).body(AppConfigResponse.class);
}
```

Add this static import:

```java
import static org.mockito.Mockito.doReturn;
```

Keep your mocks as:

```java
@Mock
private RestClient partnerRepoClient;

@Mock
private RestClient.RequestHeadersUriSpec<?> requestHeadersUriSpec;

@Mock
private RestClient.RequestHeadersSpec<?> requestHeadersSpec;

@Mock
private RestClient.ResponseSpec responseSpec;
```

Use the same fix in the user test:

```java
@Test
void shouldGetUserByIdSuccessfully() {
    UserResponse expectedResponse = new UserResponse();
    expectedResponse.setUserId("testuser");
    expectedResponse.setUsername("testuser");

    doReturn(requestHeadersUriSpec)
            .when(partnerRepoClient)
            .get();

    doReturn(requestHeadersSpec)
            .when(requestHeadersUriSpec)
            .uri(
                    "http://partner-repository/users/{userId}",
                    "testuser"
            );

    when(requestHeadersSpec.retrieve())
            .thenReturn(responseSpec);

    when(responseSpec.body(UserResponse.class))
            .thenReturn(expectedResponse);

    UserResponse result =
            partnerRepositoryClient.getUserById("testuser");

    assertEquals("testuser", result.getUserId());
    assertEquals("testuser", result.getUsername());
}
```

The production code does not need changing. This is only Mockito struggling with Spring RestClient’s self-referencing wildcard generics.
